  "text": "How can the discrepancy between in vitro inhibition of miR10a expression with antagomiRs versus genetic ablation be explained? It is possible that antagomiR-10a had off-target effects, e.g. inhibition of miR-10b and miR-125a, which has sequence homology or interaction with other targets. In fact, antagomiR125a did reduce FoxP3 expression to some extent (although to a lesser degree than antagomiR-10a) but the combination of antagomiR-10a and antagomiR-125a did not further enhance FoxP3 downregulation (data not shown). Alternatively, miR-10b might compensate for the absence of miR-10a in miR-10a-deficient Treg, since miRNAs are often redundant [CITATION_1] . Temporally controlled conditional miR-10a ablation might reveal its function [CITATION_2] . Finally, miR-10a might be expressed and functional only in a subset of Treg as it has become clear that CD4 + CD25",
